│ THOUGHT: Now I'm getting somewhere! Look at line 17547: `bool IsSignedVal = !isKnownNonNegative(V, SimplifyQuery(*DL));` This checks if a value is signed (i.e., might be negative). Then at line 17548: `if   │
│ ((!IsSignedNode || IsSignedVal) && OrigBitWidth > BitWidth) {`                                                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ The logic seems to be checking if a value can be truncated. But for `zext`, we have a different issue: `zext` of a negative value produces a large positive value, not a negative value. So when we demote     │
│ `zext i16 -1 to i32` (value 65535) to i16, we get -1, which is wrong.                                                                                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ The issue is that `zext` changes the interpretation of the bits. When we have `zext i16 -1 to i32`:                                                                                                            │
│ - i16 -1 = 0xFFFF (all bits set)                                                                                                                                                                               │
│ - After zext to i32 = 0x0000FFFF (lower 16 bits set)                                                                                                                                                           │
│ - Value = 65535 (unsigned)                                                                                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ If we truncate this back to i16, we get 0xFFFF = -1 (signed), which is different from the original i16 value in terms of signed interpretation.                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ The fix should be in how `zext` is handled. When we have `zext`, we should check if the source value might be negative. If it might be, we shouldn't demote it because the zero-extension changes the value's  │
│ interpretation.                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ Actually, looking back at the code in `vectorizeTree` for the cast operations, I think the issue is simpler. When `BWSz == SrcBWSz` and we convert `zext` to `BitCast`, we lose the zero-extension semantics.  │
│ We should keep it as `zext` even if it's a no-op (zext from i16 to i16).                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
│ Let me implement a simpler fix. In the `vectorizeTree` function, when we have `zext` or `sext` and `BWSz == SrcBWSz`, we should not convert to `BitCast`. We should keep the original opcode:                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                                                                │
